    marks: 2, estimatedTimeMinutes: 3,
    question: "What is a selectively permeable membrane? Why is the plasma membrane described as selectively permeable?",
    answer: "A selectively permeable (semi-permeable) membrane is a membrane that allows certain substances to pass through it while restricting the passage of others. It does not allow everything through — only certain molecules and ions are permitted, depending on their size, charge, and chemical nature.\n\nThe plasma membrane is selectively permeable because:\n1. It allows small, non-polar molecules (e.g., oxygen, carbon dioxide, water) to pass freely through the phospholipid bilayer.\n2. It restricts large molecules (proteins, polysaccharides), charged ions, and certain polar molecules, controlling their entry and exit through specific protein channels and carrier proteins.\nThis selective permeability allows the cell to maintain a stable internal environment (homeostasis), absorb nutrients, and expel waste products in a controlled manner.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Define selectively permeable", explanation: "Allows certain substances to pass; restricts others." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "What passes freely", explanation: "Small non-polar molecules: O₂, CO₂, water." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "What is restricted", explanation: "Large molecules, ions, certain polar molecules — pass only through specific channels." },
    ],
    hint: "Think about what 'selective' means — it doesn't block everything, and it doesn't let everything through.",
