    question: "Define osmosis. In which direction does water move during osmosis?",
    answer: "Osmosis is the spontaneous movement (diffusion) of water molecules from a region of higher water concentration (lower solute concentration / hypotonic solution) to a region of lower water concentration (higher solute concentration / hypertonic solution) through a selectively permeable membrane, until equilibrium is reached.\n\nDirection of water movement:\n• Water always moves from the hypotonic solution (lower solute) to the hypertonic solution (higher solute) — i.e., from where water is more concentrated to where it is less concentrated.\n• This movement is passive — it requires no energy (ATP).",
