    difficulty: "Medium", bloomsLevel: "understand",
    marks: 3, estimatedTimeMinutes: 4,
    question: "Compare the plasma membrane and cell wall in plant cells in terms of: (a) chemical composition, (b) permeability, (c) presence in different organisms.",
    answer: "(a) Chemical composition:\n• Plasma membrane: Composed of a phospholipid bilayer with embedded proteins and carbohydrates (fluid mosaic model, Singer and Nicolson, 1972). Main components: phospholipids, proteins, cholesterol, glycoproteins.\n• Cell wall: Composed mainly of cellulose (a polysaccharide) in plant cells. In bacteria, the cell wall is made of peptidoglycan; in fungi, it is made of chitin.\n\n(b) Permeability:\n• Plasma membrane: Selectively (semi-) permeable — controls which substances enter and exit the cell. Water, O₂, CO₂ pass freely; large molecules and ions need channels/pumps.\n• Cell wall: Fully permeable — allows all substances to pass through freely. It provides no selectivity barrier.\n\n(c) Presence:\n• Plasma membrane: Present in ALL cells — plant, animal, bacterial, fungal, and all other living cells.\n• Cell wall: Present in plant cells, fungal cells, and most bacterial cells. ABSENT in animal cells.",
