    difficulty: "Easy", bloomsLevel: "remember",
    marks: 3, estimatedTimeMinutes: 4,
    question: "Describe the structure of the plasma membrane according to the Fluid Mosaic Model. Who proposed this model?",
    answer: "The Fluid Mosaic Model was proposed by Singer and Nicolson in 1972.\n\nStructure of the plasma membrane:\n1. Phospholipid bilayer: The basic framework is a double layer of phospholipid molecules. Each phospholipid has a hydrophilic (water-loving) 'head' and two hydrophobic (water-repelling) fatty acid 'tails.' The heads of both layers face outward (toward the water on both sides) and the tails face inward — away from water.\n2. Proteins: Protein molecules are embedded in or associated with the phospholipid bilayer. Integral (intrinsic) proteins are embedded within the bilayer; peripheral (extrinsic) proteins are loosely attached to the surface. They function as channels, carriers, receptors, and enzymes.\n3. Carbohydrates: Short carbohydrate chains (oligosaccharides) are attached to lipids (forming glycolipids) or proteins (forming glycoproteins) on the outer surface. They are involved in cell recognition and communication.\n4. 'Fluid': The phospholipids and proteins can move laterally within the bilayer — the membrane is not rigid but fluid, like a liquid crystal.\n5. 'Mosaic': The various proteins embedded in the bilayer create a mosaic (patchwork) appearance.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Proposed by", explanation: "Singer and Nicolson, 1972." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Phospholipid bilayer", explanation: "Double layer; hydrophilic heads out, hydrophobic tails inward." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Proteins", explanation: "Integral (embedded) and peripheral (surface) proteins — channels, carriers, receptors." },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: "Carbohydrates", explanation: "Glycoproteins and glycolipids on outer surface — cell recognition." },
      { stepNumber: 5, title: "Fluid + Mosaic", explanation: "Fluid: components can move laterally. Mosaic: protein patchwork in the bilayer." },
    ],
    hint: "The two key words are 'Fluid' and 'Mosaic' — understand what each word refers to in the membrane structure.",
