    answer: "(a) RBC in distilled water (hypotonic solution):\n• Water enters the RBC by osmosis → cell swells → the RBC bursts (haemolysis/cytolysis).\n• Animal cells have no cell wall to resist the osmotic entry of water.\n\n(b) RBC in concentrated salt solution (hypertonic solution):\n• Water exits the RBC by osmosis → cell loses water → RBC shrinks and becomes crenated (crinkled/spiky shape).\n\nComparison with plant cells:\n(a) In distilled water:\n• Plant cell: Water enters by osmosis → cell swells → becomes turgid — but does NOT burst. The rigid cellulose cell wall exerts an opposing wall pressure equal to osmotic pressure when fully turgid, preventing bursting.\n\n(b) In concentrated salt solution:\n• Plant cell: Water exits by osmosis → protoplasm shrinks and pulls away from cell wall → plasmolysis. The cell wall remains intact.\n\nKey difference — the cell wall:\nAnimal cells lack a cell wall. Plant cells have a rigid cellulose cell wall that (1) prevents lysis in hypotonic conditions by exerting wall pressure, and (2) causes the characteristic plasmolysis appearance in hypertonic conditions, where the plasma membrane separates from the wall. The cell wall is the structural reason for the different behaviours.",
