    marks: 3, estimatedTimeMinutes: 5,
    question: "Explain why a plant wilts when it has not been watered for several days. Use the terms 'osmosis,' 'turgidity,' and 'turgor pressure' in your answer.",
    answer: "In a well-watered plant, cells are turgid — the vacuoles and cytoplasm are full of water, creating an outward pressure on the cell wall called turgor pressure. This turgor pressure keeps plant tissues firm and rigid, supporting the plant's structure.\n\nWhen the plant is not watered:\n1. The plant loses water through transpiration (evaporation from leaves) continuously.\n2. As cells lose water, the water content of the cell decreases. The cell's internal solution becomes relatively more concentrated.\n3. If water is not replenished from the soil, the concentration of the soil solution may become equal to or greater than the cell's internal solution.\n4. By osmosis, there is no net inward movement of water; water may even move out of cells.\n5. The vacuoles lose water → cells are no longer full → turgidity decreases → turgor pressure drops.\n6. Without turgor pressure to maintain rigidity, the plant tissues cannot support themselves → the plant wilts.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Normal turgid state", explanation: "Full vacuoles → turgor pressure pushes cell wall → plant stays rigid." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "When not watered", explanation: "Transpiration removes water; no replenishment from soil." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Osmosis stops or reverses", explanation: "Cell contents become concentrated; net water movement out or stops → cells lose water." },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: "Loss of turgidity", explanation: "Vacuoles deflate → turgor pressure drops → cells become flaccid." },
      { stepNumber: 5, title: "Wilting", explanation: "No turgor pressure → plant cannot maintain rigidity → wilts." },
    ],
    hint: "Think about what keeps a plant upright — it's not a skeleton, it's something inside the cells. What happens to that when the cells dry out?",
