    question: "A student forgot to label three beakers containing different solutions: pure water, 0.9% salt solution, and 10% salt solution. She places identical fresh carrot strips into each beaker for 30 minutes. Carrot A becomes very firm, Carrot B stays the same size, Carrot C becomes soft and limp. Match each carrot to its beaker and explain the osmotic process in each case.",
    answer: "Carrot A (very firm) → Pure water (hypotonic solution):\nThe water outside has a higher water concentration than the carrot cells' internal contents. Water enters the carrot cells by osmosis through the selectively permeable plasma membrane. Cells become turgid → carrot becomes firm.\n\nCarrot B (unchanged) → 0.9% salt solution (isotonic solution):\nThe concentration of the salt solution is approximately equal to the concentration inside the carrot cells. There is no net movement of water by osmosis. Cells maintain their existing water content → carrot is unchanged.\n\nCarrot C (soft and limp) → 10% salt solution (hypertonic solution):\nThe salt solution has a much higher solute concentration (lower water concentration) than the carrot cells. Water exits the carrot cells by osmosis. Cells lose water → plasmolysis occurs → cells become flaccid → carrot becomes soft and limp.",
