    questionType: "competency", questionFormat: "LongAnswer",
    difficulty: "Medium", bloomsLevel: "analyse",
    marks: 4, estimatedTimeMinutes: 7,
    question: "A nurse must prepare an intravenous (IV) fluid for a patient. She has three solutions available: (a) distilled water, (b) 0.9% saline (normal saline), (c) 10% glucose. Which solution should she use, and why? What would happen to the patient's red blood cells if she used each of the other two solutions by mistake?",
    answer: "Correct choice: (b) 0.9% normal saline (isotonic solution).\n\nReason: Normal saline has the same osmotic concentration as blood plasma and red blood cells. When RBCs are in an isotonic solution, there is no net movement of water by osmosis. RBCs maintain their normal shape, size, and function.\n\nIf (a) distilled water was used by mistake:\n• Distilled water is hypotonic relative to RBCs.\n• Water enters RBCs by osmosis → RBCs swell → RBCs burst (haemolysis).\n• Large-scale haemolysis destroys red blood cells, releasing haemoglobin into the blood plasma.\n• This causes severe haemolytic anaemia and can be fatal.\n\nIf (c) 10% glucose was used by mistake:\n• 10% glucose is hypertonic relative to RBCs (much more concentrated than blood).\n• Water exits RBCs by osmosis → RBCs lose water → RBCs shrink and crenate (crinkle).\n• Crenated RBCs cannot carry oxygen effectively.\n• Can cause cellular dehydration and circulatory failure.\n\nConclusion: Only an isotonic solution is safe for IV use, as it causes no osmotic stress on blood cells.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Correct choice", explanation: "0.9% normal saline — isotonic with RBCs, no net osmosis." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Distilled water error", explanation: "Hypotonic → water enters RBCs → haemolysis → potentially fatal." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "10% glucose error", explanation: "Hypertonic → water exits RBCs → crenation → cells cannot function." },
    ],
    hint: "Think about what 'isotonic' means for a cell — what happens when there is no net osmosis?",
