    question: "Why is the nucleus called the 'control centre' of the cell? State two reasons.",
    answer: "The nucleus is called the 'control centre' of the cell because:\n\n1. Contains genetic information: The nucleus houses the chromosomes (made of DNA and histone proteins) that carry all the genetic instructions for the cell. These instructions determine which proteins are made, and therefore control all cellular activities — growth, metabolism, reproduction, and differentiation.\n\n2. Controls protein synthesis: The nucleus transcribes DNA into mRNA (messenger RNA), which exits through nuclear pores and carries instructions to ribosomes in the cytoplasm. Protein synthesis on ribosomes is thus directed by the nucleus. Since proteins (enzymes, structural proteins, signalling molecules) control all cellular reactions, the nucleus ultimately controls all cell activity.\n\nEvidence: When the nucleus is removed from a cell (e.g., in experiments with Amoeba), the cell gradually loses its ability to perform vital functions and eventually dies — confirming the nucleus is essential for cell regulation.",
