    answer: "Mitochondria are called the 'powerhouse of the cell' because they are the primary site of aerobic cellular respiration — the process by which glucose and oxygen are used to produce ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the universal energy currency of the cell.\n\nKey points:\n• Mitochondria carry out the Krebs cycle (in the matrix) and oxidative phosphorylation (on the inner membrane — cristae).\n• These processes convert the chemical energy stored in food (glucose) into ATP, releasing CO₂ and water as by-products.\n• The folded inner membrane (cristae) provides a large surface area for ATP synthesis, maximising energy production.\n• Most cellular activities — muscle contraction, active transport, protein synthesis — are powered by the ATP produced in mitochondria.\n\nWithout mitochondria, cells would rely only on glycolysis (anaerobic respiration), which produces far less ATP per glucose molecule.",
