    question: "What are lysosomes? Why are they called the 'suicidal bags' of the cell?",
    answer: "Lysosomes are membrane-bound sac-like organelles found in the cytoplasm of eukaryotic cells. They contain powerful hydrolytic (digestive) enzymes that can break down all types of biological macromolecules — proteins, carbohydrates, lipids, and nucleic acids.\n\nNormal functions:\n• Intracellular digestion of food particles and foreign material (phagocytosis).\n• Digestion of worn-out or damaged organelles (autophagy).\n• Destruction of pathogens engulfed by white blood cells.\n\nWhy called 'suicidal bags':\n• During cell damage, cellular stress, or during programmed cell death (apoptosis/autolysis), the lysosomal membranes rupture and release their digestive enzymes into the cytoplasm.\n• These enzymes then digest (self-destroy) the entire contents of the cell — effectively causing the cell's own death from within.\n• This self-destruction is sometimes biologically necessary — e.g., removing the tail of a tadpole during metamorphosis, or removing the webbing between fingers during human fetal development.",
