    question: "Compare Rough Endoplasmic Reticulum (RER) and Smooth Endoplasmic Reticulum (SER) in terms of structure and function.",
    answer: "Comparison of RER and SER:\n\nStructure:\n• Rough ER (RER): Ribosomes are attached to the outer surface → gives a 'rough' or granular appearance under the electron microscope.\n• Smooth ER (SER): No ribosomes on the surface → appears smooth.\nBoth are made of interconnected membrane-bound cisternae (flattened sacs) and tubules.\n\nFunction:\n• Rough ER (RER):\n  - Site of synthesis of proteins that are destined for secretion (exported from the cell), for the cell membrane, or for lysosomes.\n  - Ribosomes on the surface synthesise proteins that are threaded into the ER lumen as they are made.\n  - Transports proteins to the Golgi apparatus for further processing.\n  - Involved in formation of new membrane material.\n\n• Smooth ER (SER):\n  - Synthesis of lipids, phospholipids, and steroids (e.g., sex hormones in gonads).\n  - Detoxification of drugs and harmful substances (especially in liver cells).\n  - Regulates calcium ion concentration in muscle cells (important for muscle contraction).\n  - Does NOT synthesise proteins.",
