    difficulty: "Easy", bloomsLevel: "remember",
    marks: 2, estimatedTimeMinutes: 3,
    question: "State two differences between the nucleus of a eukaryotic cell and the nucleoid region of a prokaryotic cell.",
    answer: "Two differences between nucleus (eukaryote) and nucleoid (prokaryote):\n\n1. Nuclear membrane:\n• Eukaryotic nucleus: Enclosed by a double membrane called the nuclear envelope (nuclear membrane), with nuclear pores for controlled transport.\n• Prokaryotic nucleoid: Not enclosed by any membrane — the DNA lies directly in the cytoplasm in a region called the nucleoid. There is no nuclear membrane.\n\n2. DNA structure:\n• Eukaryotic nucleus: Contains multiple linear (unbranched) chromosomes composed of DNA + histone proteins (chromatin).\n• Prokaryotic nucleoid: Contains a single circular DNA molecule with no associated histone proteins (naked DNA, though there are some DNA-binding proteins).",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Difference 1 — Nuclear membrane", explanation: "Eukaryote: nuclear membrane present. Prokaryote: no nuclear membrane (nucleoid in cytoplasm)." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Difference 2 — DNA structure", explanation: "Eukaryote: multiple linear chromosomes + histones. Prokaryote: single circular DNA, no histones." },
    ],
    hint: "The most important difference is the nuclear membrane. What else differs — how the DNA is organised?",
