    answer: "Functions of the Golgi apparatus:\n1. Receives proteins and lipids packaged in vesicles from the Endoplasmic Reticulum (via the 'cis' face).\n2. Modifies and processes these molecules (e.g., adds sugar groups — glycosylation, cuts and folds proteins).\n3. Sorts and packages them into vesicles for specific destinations — secretion from the cell (exocytosis), delivery to the cell membrane, or formation of lysosomes.\n4. Forms primary lysosomes (sacs of hydrolytic enzymes).\n5. Produces the cell plate (new cell wall material) during plant cell division.\n\nWhy called the 'post office':\n• Like a post office, the Golgi apparatus receives 'packages' (proteins/lipids from the ER), processes and addresses them (modifies and sorts), and dispatches them to their correct destination (secretion, cell membrane, lysosomes).\n• It is the cell's central sorting and dispatching centre for proteins and lipids.",
