    difficulty: "Medium", bloomsLevel: "understand",
    marks: 2, estimatedTimeMinutes: 3,
    question: "State two similarities between plastids and mitochondria.",
    answer: "Two similarities between plastids (e.g., chloroplasts) and mitochondria:\n\n1. Both are semi-autonomous organelles:\n• Both plastids and mitochondria contain their own circular DNA (like prokaryotic DNA) and 70S ribosomes (prokaryotic type). This means they can synthesise some of their own proteins independently of the cell's nuclear DNA.\n• This semi-autonomy makes them partially independent of the cell's nucleus for their maintenance and division.\n\n2. Both have a double membrane:\n• Both organelles are enclosed by two membrane layers — an outer membrane and an inner membrane.\n• In mitochondria, the inner membrane is folded into cristae. In chloroplasts, the inner membrane encloses the stroma; within the stroma, thylakoid membranes are further organised into grana.\n\nSignificance: These similarities are the basis of the endosymbiont theory (proposed by Lynn Margulis) — both organelles are believed to have evolved from ancient prokaryotic cells that were engulfed by a host eukaryotic cell and established a permanent symbiotic relationship.",
