    topicId: "t3", topicName: "Cell Organelles",
    questionType: "competency", questionFormat: "ShortAnswer",
    difficulty: "Easy", bloomsLevel: "apply",
    marks: 3, estimatedTimeMinutes: 5,
    question: "A pharmaceutical company wants to produce large quantities of a hormone protein (like insulin) using genetically engineered cells. A biotechnologist recommends using a cell line with many ribosomes, well-developed RER, and an active Golgi apparatus. Explain why each of these three features is important for this purpose.",
    answer: "For large-scale secretory protein (hormone) production, three cellular features are essential:\n\n1. Many ribosomes:\n• All proteins are synthesised on ribosomes by translating mRNA into polypeptide chains.\n• More ribosomes = greater capacity for protein synthesis per unit time.\n• For high-volume hormone production, a large number of ribosomes is the primary requirement.\n\n2. Well-developed Rough ER (RER):\n• Secretory proteins are synthesised on ribosomes that are attached to the RER.\n• As the protein is synthesised, it is threaded into the RER lumen, where it undergoes initial folding and quality control.\n• The RER then packages the correctly folded protein into transport vesicles for delivery to the Golgi apparatus.\n• More developed RER = greater capacity to handle protein folding and transport.\n\n3. Active Golgi apparatus:\n• The Golgi receives transport vesicles from the RER, further modifies the proteins (e.g., glycosylation, cleavage of signal peptides), sorts, and packages them into secretory vesicles.\n• Secretory vesicles fuse with the plasma membrane (exocytosis), releasing the hormone outside the cell.\n• An active Golgi processes more proteins per unit time and ensures correct modification for biological activity.\n\nSummary: The three organelles form the secretory pathway: RER (synthesis + folding) → Golgi (modification + packaging) → secretory vesicle (release). All three must be active for efficient hormone production.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Many ribosomes", explanation: "Ribosomes are where proteins are made. More ribosomes = more protein synthesis capacity." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Well-developed RER", explanation: "Secretory proteins are made on RER-bound ribosomes. RER folds proteins and packages them for Golgi." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Active Golgi", explanation: "Modifies, sorts, packages proteins into secretory vesicles → releases hormone via exocytosis." },
    ],
    hint: "Trace the journey of a secretory protein from its synthesis to its release: where is it made? Where is it processed? How does it get out of the cell?",
