    marks: 2, estimatedTimeMinutes: 4,
    question: "A newly discovered cell has large central vacuoles, a cellulose cell wall, but NO plastids. Is this cell plant or animal? Can it perform photosynthesis? Justify your reasoning.",
    answer: "This cell is a PLANT cell.\n\nJustification:\n• Cellulose cell wall: Present only in plant cells (and bacteria/fungi, but with different composition). Animal cells never have a cellulose cell wall. This is a definitive feature of a plant cell.\n• Large central vacuole: Characteristic of plant cells. Animal cells do not have a large central vacuole.\n• Both features together: Clearly indicate a plant cell.\n\nCan it perform photosynthesis? NO.\n• Photosynthesis requires chloroplasts, specifically the chlorophyll pigment contained within them.\n• This cell has no plastids — therefore no chloroplasts — therefore no chlorophyll.\n• Without chlorophyll, the cell cannot absorb light energy, and photosynthesis cannot occur.\n\nThis type of plantcell (without plastids) is typical of underground or non-photosynthetic plant organs — for example, root cells. Root cells are plant cells that are never exposed to light and therefore do not develop chloroplasts. They have cell walls and vacuoles but no chloroplasts.",
