    difficulty: "Medium", bloomsLevel: "analyse",
    marks: 4, estimatedTimeMinutes: 7,
    question: "A doctor examines a biopsy and finds that the phagocytic immune cells (cells that engulf and destroy bacteria) in the sample have very few or no functional lysosomes. What problem would these cells face? Why would this be dangerous for the patient? Name any known human condition where lysosome dysfunction occurs.",
    answer: "Problem the phagocytic cells would face:\n• Normal phagocytic cells (neutrophils, macrophages) engulf bacteria through phagocytosis, forming membrane-bound vesicles called phagosomes.\n• Lysosomes normally fuse with phagosomes to form phagolysosomes. The hydrolytic enzymes in the lysosomes then digest and destroy the engulfed bacteria.\n• Without functional lysosomes, the phagocytic cells CANNOT digest the engulfed bacteria.\n• The bacteria remain alive inside the phagosomes, potentially multiplying.\n• The immune system's primary mechanism for destroying pathogens is severely impaired.\n\nDanger to the patient:\n• The patient's immune system would be unable to effectively eliminate bacterial (and other) infections.\n• Even normally harmless environmental bacteria could cause life-threatening infections (opportunistic infections).\n• This constitutes a primary immunodeficiency — the patient would be highly susceptible to repeated, severe infections that are difficult or impossible to treat with standard approaches.\n\nKnown human condition:\n• Chediak-Higashi Syndrome: A rare inherited disease where lysosomes fail to fuse properly with phagosomes in immune cells. Patients have severely impaired immunity and suffer from recurrent life-threatening bacterial infections.\n• Also: Lysosomal storage diseases (e.g., Tay-Sachs disease, Gaucher's disease) involve enzyme deficiencies within lysosomes, causing toxic accumulation of undigested materials in cells.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Normal lysosome function in phagocytes", explanation: "Phagocyte engulfs bacteria → phagosome + lysosome → phagolysosomes → enzymes destroy bacteria." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Without functional lysosomes", explanation: "Bacteria survive inside phagosomes → immune cells cannot destroy pathogens." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Danger to patient", explanation: "Severe immunodeficiency → life-threatening infections from normally harmless organisms." },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: "Known condition", explanation: "Chediak-Higashi Syndrome — lysosome-phagosome fusion defect → immunodeficiency." },
    ],
    hint: "Think step by step: what do phagocytes normally do after engulfing a bacterium? Which organelle is responsible for the final killing step? What happens if that organelle is missing?",
