    difficulty: "Medium", bloomsLevel: "analyse",
    marks: 4, estimatedTimeMinutes: 7,
    question: "Scientists have found that both mitochondria and chloroplasts contain circular DNA and 70S ribosomes — features normally associated with bacteria. Based on this evidence, what hypothesis would you formulate about the evolutionary origin of these organelles? How does this hypothesis support cell theory?",
    answer: "Hypothesis formulated: Endosymbiont Theory (Endosymbiosis).\n\nThe evidence (circular DNA, 70S ribosomes, double membrane, ability to divide by binary fission — similar to bacteria) supports the hypothesis that mitochondria and chloroplasts originated from ancient free-living prokaryotic cells:\n• Mitochondria: ancestral aerobic bacterium (similar to alpha-proteobacteria).\n• Chloroplasts: ancestral photosynthetic bacterium (similar to Cyanobacteria).\n\nProposed mechanism:\n• Approximately 1.5–2 billion years ago, an ancestral eukaryotic host cell (or proto-eukaryote) engulfed a prokaryotic bacterium — but instead of digesting it, the bacterium survived inside the host.\n• A mutualistic (symbiotic) relationship developed: the bacterium provided ATP (aerobic respiration) or photosynthates to the host, while the host provided shelter, nutrients, and a protected environment.\n• Over evolutionary time, the endosymbiont lost the ability to live independently and became a permanent organelle.\n\nEvidence supporting the hypothesis:\n• Own circular DNA (like prokaryotes, not linear like eukaryotic nuclear DNA)\n• 70S ribosomes (prokaryotic type — inhibited by the same antibiotics that kill bacteria, e.g., chloramphenicol)\n• Double membrane (inner = original prokaryote membrane; outer = derived from host engulfment by phagocytosis)\n• Divide by binary fission (like bacteria), not mitosis\n\nHow it supports cell theory:\n• The endosymbiont hypothesis directly supports Virchow's postulate: 'All cells arise from pre-existing cells.'\n• The engulfed prokaryotic cells were themselves cells — they arose from pre-existing cells.\n• Over evolutionary time, these cells became integrated into eukaryotic cells, demonstrating that even complex organelles have cellular origins — consistent with the principle that all cellular structures ultimately derive from pre-existing cells.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "State the hypothesis", explanation: "Endosymbiont theory: mitochondria and chloroplasts evolved from engulfed prokaryotic bacteria." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Evidence", explanation: "Circular DNA, 70S ribosomes, double membrane, binary fission — all prokaryotic features." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Mechanism", explanation: "Host engulfed bacterium → mutualistic symbiosis developed → bacterium became permanent organelle." },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: "Connection to cell theory", explanation: "Endosymbionts were cells → Virchow's postulate (cells from cells) applies even to organelle evolution." },
    ],
    hint: "The features listed (circular DNA, 70S ribosomes) are found in bacteria, not eukaryotic cell organelles normally. What does this suggest about where these organelles came from?",
    keyConcepts: ["endosymbiont theory", "mitochondria origin", "chloroplast origin", "prokaryote", "circular DNA", "70S ribosomes", "cell theory"],
    conceptsCovered: ["bio:9:ch01:mitochondria-powerhouse", "bio:9:ch01:plastid-types", "bio:9:ch01:cell-theory-postulates"],
