    marks: 4, estimatedTimeMinutes: 7,
    question: "In cells that produce and secrete large amounts of proteins (e.g., pancreatic cells secreting digestive enzymes), a biologist observes: a large nucleus, a prominent nucleolus, abundant RER, and a well-developed Golgi apparatus. Explain why each of these features is expected in a highly secretory cell.",
    answer: "Each structural feature reflects a high demand for protein secretion:\n\n1. Large nucleus:\n• Secretory cells must continuously transcribe large amounts of mRNA for the secretory proteins.\n• A larger nucleus contains more active chromatin regions and more transcription machinery (RNA polymerases, transcription factors).\n• More transcription → more mRNA → more protein production capacity.\n\n2. Prominent nucleolus:\n• The nucleolus is the site of rRNA synthesis and ribosome subunit assembly.\n• A larger, more prominent nucleolus indicates higher ribosome production.\n• More ribosomes are needed to translate the large quantities of mRNA for secretory proteins.\n• A prominent nucleolus reflects high ribosome demand for a high-protein-output cell.\n\n3. Abundant RER:\n• Secretory proteins are synthesised on ribosomes attached to the RER.\n• Abundant RER provides more surface area for ribosome attachment → more simultaneous protein synthesis.\n• RER lumen is also where protein folding, quality control, and initial post-translational modifications occur.\n• More RER = more capacity for correct protein folding and packaging into transport vesicles for the Golgi.\n\n4. Well-developed Golgi apparatus:\n• All secretory proteins pass through the Golgi for further modification (glycosylation, cleavage), sorting by destination, and packaging into secretory vesicles.\n• A larger, more active Golgi processes more proteins per unit time and ensures correct targeting for secretion via exocytosis.\n• Well-developed Golgi = high throughput of secretory proteins.\n\nThe four features form a coordinated secretory pathway: Nucleus (transcription → mRNA) → RER ribosomes (translation → protein) → Golgi (processing and packaging) → secretory vesicle (exocytosis).",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Large nucleus", explanation: "More transcription of mRNA for secretory proteins." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Prominent nucleolus", explanation: "More rRNA synthesis → more ribosomes assembled → needed for high-volume protein synthesis." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Abundant RER", explanation: "More sites for secretory protein synthesis, folding, and transport vesicle formation." },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: "Well-developed Golgi", explanation: "Higher throughput for protein modification, sorting, and packaging for secretion." },
    ],
    hint: "Trace the journey of a protein from gene to secretion. Which organelle is involved at each step, and why would a secretory cell need more of each?",
