    question: "What is the significance of the nuclear membrane? Briefly describe its structure. [2 marks]",
    answer: "Significance of the nuclear membrane (nuclear envelope):\n1. Protects the nucleus and its DNA from the cytoplasm — separates nuclear contents from cytoplasmic enzymes and maintains a distinct nuclear environment for gene expression.\n2. Regulates transport: Controls the movement of molecules (mRNA, ribosomal subunits, proteins) between nucleus and cytoplasm through nuclear pore complexes — essential for controlling gene expression.\n3. Allows post-transcriptional processing: By separating transcription (nucleus) from translation (cytoplasm), the nuclear membrane allows mRNA to be processed (capping, splicing, poly-A addition) before reaching ribosomes — increasing accuracy of protein synthesis.\n\nStructure of the nuclear membrane:\n• Double membrane: Two parallel lipid bilayer membranes — the outer nuclear membrane (continuous with the RER) and the inner nuclear membrane, separated by the perinuclear space.\n• Nuclear pores: Large protein complexes (nuclear pore complexes, NPC) that perforate both membranes and allow selective, regulated transport of molecules in both directions.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Significance", explanation: "Protects DNA; regulates transport between nucleus and cytoplasm; enables mRNA processing." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Structure", explanation: "Double membrane (inner + outer); outer connected to RER; nuclear pores for transport." },
    ],
    hint: "Two parts to answer: (1) why is the nuclear membrane important? (2) what does it look like? Keep each part concise.",
