    marks: 4, estimatedTimeMinutes: 10,
    question: "Cells undergoing programmed cell death (apoptosis) show two key events: (i) cytochrome c is released from mitochondria, and (ii) lysosomes release their enzymes. Explain how each event contributes to the orderly self-destruction of the cell during apoptosis.",
    answer: "Apoptosis is controlled, orderly cell death — essential for development and homeostasis. It differs from necrosis (accidental cell death), which causes inflammation.\n\n(i) Cytochrome c release from mitochondria:\n• Cytochrome c is normally a component of the electron transport chain inside the inner mitochondrial membrane, involved in ATP production.\n• In apoptosis, cellular signals (e.g., DNA damage, growth factor withdrawal) cause proteins of the Bcl-2 family to form pores in the outer mitochondrial membrane.\n• Cytochrome c leaks from the intermembrane space into the cytoplasm.\n• In the cytoplasm, cytochrome c combines with other proteins (Apaf-1, procaspase-9) to form the 'apoptosome' complex.\n• The apoptosome activates caspase-9, which then activates downstream executioner caspases (caspase-3, -6, -7).\n• These caspases are proteases that systematically cleave specific cellular proteins: nuclear lamins (causing nuclear condensation and fragmentation), cytoskeletal proteins (causing cell shrinkage), and DNA repair enzymes (allowing DNA degradation).\n• Result: Ordered protein digestion and nuclear breakdown — a controlled dismantling of the cell from the inside.\n\n(ii) Lysosome enzyme release (lysosomal membrane permeabilisation):\n• Lysosomal membranes become destabilised and more permeable during apoptosis.\n• Cathepsins (lysosomal cysteine and serine proteases) are released from lysosomes into the cytoplasm.\n• Cathepsins degrade cytoplasmic proteins and organellar components, and can activate additional caspases, amplifying the apoptotic signal.\n• Lysosomal enzymes also participate in the final digestion of cellular contents.\n\n'Orderly' destruction — why it doesn't cause inflammation:\n• The cell packages its fragmented contents into membrane-bound 'apoptotic bodies' (cellular remnants enclosed in plasma membrane).\n• These apoptotic bodies are rapidly engulfed by neighbouring cells or macrophages through phagocytosis.\n• No cellular contents are released into the surrounding tissue, so no inflammatory response is triggered — unlike necrosis, where the cell bursts and releases its contents into the tissue.\n\nConclusion: Cytochrome c (via caspase cascade) and lysosomal enzymes (via direct protein digestion) work sequentially to systematically dismantle the cell's components in a controlled manner, ensuring cell death without collateral tissue damage.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Cytochrome c — mechanism", explanation: "Released from mitochondria → forms apoptosome → activates caspases → caspases cleave structural proteins → orderly cellular dismantling." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "Lysosome — mechanism", explanation: "Membranes permeabilised → cathepsins released → digest cytoplasmic proteins → amplify apoptotic signals." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Why 'orderly'", explanation: "Cell packs contents into apoptotic bodies → engulfed by neighbours/macrophages → no inflammatory response." },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: "Contrast with necrosis", explanation: "Necrosis: cell bursts, releases contents, causes inflammation. Apoptosis: controlled, no inflammation." },
    ],
    hint: "Cytochrome c is from mitochondria — it usually helps make ATP. In apoptosis, why would its release from mitochondria trigger cell death?",
    hint2: "The caspase cascade is key: cytochrome c → apoptosome → caspase-9 → executioner caspases → protein/DNA digestion.",
    hint3: "For lysosomes: they contain digestive enzymes normally kept safely inside membranes. In apoptosis, what happens when these membranes become leaky?",
    examTip: "This is a beyond-NCERT HOTS question. Examiners reward structured, mechanistic answers. Use the format: event → mechanism → result.",
