    marks: 4, estimatedTimeMinutes: 10,
    question: "The Endoplasmic Reticulum (ER) forms a continuous membrane network connecting the nuclear envelope to the plasma membrane. A cell biologist describes the ER as the cell's 'internal transport highway.' Evaluate this description by explaining how the ER connects nuclear gene expression to protein secretion.",
    answer: "The description is well-justified. The ER functions as an internal transport highway connecting nuclear gene expression to the plasma membrane via the following pathway:\n\n1. Nuclear-ER physical connection:\n• The outer membrane of the nuclear envelope is directly continuous with the ER membrane (they are the same membrane). This physical continuity means the nuclear lumen and the ER lumen are connected.\n• mRNA produced in the nucleus exits through nuclear pores → enters the cytoplasm → associates with ribosomes on the RER.\n\n2. Translation on RER ribosomes:\n• Ribosomes on the outer surface of the RER translate mRNA into polypeptide chains.\n• As the polypeptide grows, it is threaded through the RER membrane into the ER lumen (co-translational translocation) — powered by signal sequences at the N-terminus of the protein.\n\n3. Protein folding and quality control:\n• Inside the RER lumen, the protein folds into its correct three-dimensional structure, assisted by molecular chaperones (e.g., BiP/GRP78).\n• Disulfide bonds form between cysteine residues.\n• Initial glycosylation (addition of oligosaccharide groups) begins here — important for protein function and targeting.\n• Misfolded proteins are retained in the ER and directed for degradation (ERAD).\n\n4. Packaging into transport vesicles:\n• Correctly folded proteins are concentrated at exit sites of the RER.\n• COPII-coated vesicles bud off from the RER, carrying the proteins to the Golgi apparatus (anterograde transport).\n\n5. Golgi processing and final dispatch:\n• Golgi apparatus receives the vesicles, further modifies and sorts the proteins, and dispatches them in secretory vesicles to the plasma membrane.\n• Exocytosis releases the secretory proteins outside the cell.\n\nConclusion: The ER functions as the essential 'highway' connecting nuclear gene expression (mRNA) → ribosomal translation → protein folding → packaging → Golgi → secretion. Without the ER's continuous membrane system, this transport pathway would not exist, and secretory protein production would be impossible.",
    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: "Nuclear-ER connection", explanation: "Outer nuclear membrane = ER membrane (continuous). mRNA exits nucleus → ribosomes on RER." },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: "RER ribosomes translate mRNA", explanation: "Protein synthesised on RER ribosomes; polypeptide threaded into ER lumen." },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: "Folding and quality control", explanation: "Protein folds in ER lumen; chaperones assist; misfolded proteins rejected (ERAD)." },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: "COPII vesicles to Golgi", explanation: "Correctly folded proteins packaged in COPII vesicles → Golgi for further processing." },
      { stepNumber: 5, title: "Golgi → secretion", explanation: "Golgi modifies, sorts → secretory vesicles → exocytosis → protein released." },
    ],
    hint: "Trace the path of a protein from the gene in the nucleus to its secretion outside the cell. What does the ER do at each stage of this journey?",
    hint2: "The outer nuclear membrane and the ER are the same membrane (physically continuous). What does this tell you about the connection between nuclear and ER functions?",
    hint3: "COPII vesicles = transport vehicles from RER to Golgi. The ER doesn't just make proteins — it's the first packaging point.",
    examTip: "Structured pathway answers (step 1 → step 2 → step 3) earn maximum marks in analytical questions. Use arrows to show the flow.",
    keyConcepts: ["ER highway", "RER", "nuclear envelope", "protein folding", "COPII vesicles", "Golgi", "secretory pathway"],
